  "prompt": "What's the size of a 4K image?",
  "response": "A 4K image typically refers to an image with a resolution of **3840 x 2160 pixels**, which is the standard for 4K Ultra HD (UHD). This resolution provides a total of **8,294,400 pixels** (approximately 8.3 megapixels).\n\nThe term \"4K\" comes from the horizontal resolution being close to 4000 pixels. In some contexts, particularly in digital cinema, 4K can also refer to **4096 x 2160 pixels** (DCI 4K), which is slightly wider and used in professional filmmaking.\n\nSo, the size of a 4K image is:\n- **3840 x 2160 pixels** (Standard 4K UHD)\n- **4096 x 2160 pixels** (DCI 4K, for cinema)",
